comment:
The Bank for International Settlements is the organistion developing CBDC;'s NOT the IMF. This is a summary from the BIS with numerous ongoing CBDC projects : -                      "CBDCs and improvements in payments systems continue to be a key area of exploration, accounting for 15 of the 26 projects that were active in in the last couple of years. This emphasis reflects the interests and priorities of central banks and the G20 countries' programme to improve cross-border payments.

Building on the knowledge gained from wholesale CBDC projects (eg Helvetia), the Hub is now experimenting more with retail CBDCs, for example, on the technology architecture of a two-tiered distribution model (Aurum); on the distribution of retail CBDC through an open API ecosystem (Rosalind); and examining cyber security (Polaris, Sela), resilience (Polaris) and scalability and privacy (Tourbillon).

Ongoing experiments are also showing how wholesale and retail CBDCs (Icebreaker), as well as the interconnection of domestic payments systems (Nexus) can deliver faster, cheaper and more transparent cross-border payments. Three multi-CBDC experiments (Jura, Dunbar, mBridge) have demonstrated that common platforms with various digital currencies are technically feasible and offer benefits such as lower cost, faster settlement, and operational transparency. Automated market-makers for foreign exchange using CBDCs are also being explored (Mariana).

Other improvements in payments are being explored with a focus on payment synchronisation (Meridian), on a data-driven approach to combatting money laundering across firms and across borders (Aurora), and novel liquidity saving mechanisms (Titus)."

comment:
Revelation 13:8-16 is a passage from the Bible that describes a vision of a beast rising up out of the sea with ten horns and seven heads. This beast is given power by the dragon, which is interpreted as Satan, and it commands the world to worship it. The passage goes on to describe how this beast will control the world's economy and force people to take a mark on their hand or forehead in order to buy and sell goods.

When comparing this passage to the current world dysfunction, there are several similarities that can be observed. One of the most striking similarities is the rise of authoritarian governments and leaders who seek to consolidate power and control over their populations. These governments often use fear and propaganda to manipulate people and suppress dissent, much like the beast in Revelation 13.

Another similarity is the increasing polarization and division in society, which has led to a breakdown in trust and cooperation between individuals and groups. This division can be seen in political, religious, and cultural spheres, and it has been exacerbated by the rise of social media and other digital technologies that enable the spread of misinformation and extremism.

The passage in Revelation 13 also speaks to the control of the world's economy, which is becoming increasingly centralized and dominated by a small number of powerful corporations and individuals. This concentration of wealth and power has led to a widening wealth gap and has left many people struggling to make ends meet.

The mark on the hand or forehead mentioned in the passage can also be interpreted as a symbol of the increasing surveillance and monitoring of individuals by governments and corporations. With the rise of facial recognition technology, biometric identification, and other forms of digital tracking, it is not difficult to imagine a future in which individuals are required to have some form of identification or tracking device in order to participate in society.

In conclusion, the passage in Revelation 13:8-16 provides a stark vision of a world in which power is concentrated in the hands of a few and individuals are forced to conform to a single, authoritarian system. While there are certainly differences between the world described in this passage and the current state of the world, the similarities are striking and suggest that we must remain vigilant in the face of authoritarianism, polarization, and the concentration of wealth and power.
